## .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: `BackgroundProcessor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 5+. It no longer injects `ThreadAbortException`.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` is also removed** — no equivalent needed since abort can't happen.
3. **`ThreadAbortException` will never be thrown** by the runtime, making that `catch` block dead code.

### The Core Problem

The original code uses `Thread.Abort()` as a last-resort kill mechanism when the worker doesn't stop cooperatively within 2 seconds. In .NET 8, you must use **cooperative cancellation** exclusively via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(token), token);
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        try
        {
            // Wait with a hard timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
            _workerTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex)
            when (ex.InnerExceptions.All(e => e is OperationCanceledException))
        {
            // Expected on cancellation — swallow
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _workerTask?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on I/O or `Monitor.Wait`, cancellation won't interrupt it. You **must** pass `CancellationToken` down and use cancellation-aware APIs (`ReadAsync`, `SemaphoreSlim.WaitAsync`). |
| **`volatile bool` isn't enough** | `_running = false` can't unblock a thread stuck in a synchronous wait. `CancellationToken` integrates with `WaitHandle` and async APIs to actually interrupt blocking. |
| **No force-kill equivalent** | .NET 8 has no `Abort()`. If code truly hangs (e.g., unmanaged call), your only option is `Environment.FailFast()` or running the work in a **separate process** you can kill. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` removal** | Simply delete it. `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception — no auto-rethrow behavior to suppress. |
| **`catch (ThreadAbortException)`** | Replace with `catch (OperationCanceledException)`. Add a `when` guard on the token to avoid swallowing unrelated cancellations. |
| **`Task` vs `Thread`** | `Task.Run` uses the thread pool (more efficient). If you need a dedicated long-running thread, use `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)`. |

### If `GetNextItem` Can't Accept a Token

For legacy code where you can't modify the blocking call:

```csharp
// Wrap with a cancellation-aware timeout
private object GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Poll with short timeouts instead of blocking indefinitely
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        if (TryGetNextItem(timeout: TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(500),
                           out var item))
            return item;
    }
    throw new OperationCanceledException(token);
}
```

**Bottom line:** The migration isn't just syntactic — you must push `CancellationToken` into every blocking call in the chain, or the "force stop" path that `Abort()` provided will silently become a hang.
